<section xml:id="sec-adjugate-matrix"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Adjugate Matrix</title>
    <introduction xml:id="sm-introduction-adjugate-matrix">
        <p>
            <idx>
                <h>Matrices</h>
                <h>Adjugate</h>
            </idx>
            For a matrix <m>A</m>, the <em>adjugate</em> matrix is the transpose of its cofactor
            matrix <m>C</m>, <m>adj(A)=C^T</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The cofactor matrix is based on cofactors and minors. Sage does not have methods to
            calculate cofactors and minors, but it can directly calculate the adjugate matrix.
        </p>
        <p>
            In Sage, the <c>adjugate()</c> method returns the adjugate matrix.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                M = matrix([
                    [1, 1, 0, 1, 2],
                    [2, 1, 1, 0, 1],
                    [1, 2, 1, 1, 0],
                    [0, 1, 2, 1, 1],
                    [1, 0, 1, 2, 1]])
                M.adjugate()
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            In the next sections, we will explore how to compute step by step the minors,
            cofactors, and then the adjugate matrix.
        </p>
    </introduction>
</section>
